article.headline: Princeton 78, Columbia 71 (OT)
article.story: NEW YORK (AP) -- Harrison Schaen made two free throws, his only points of the game, to give Princeton the lead in the first minute of overtime and the Tigers went on to a 78-71 victory over Columbia on Saturday night. Princeton (14-7, 7-1) won for the seventh time in eight games and remained in first place in the Ivy League. Columbia (6-15, 2-6) led 48-40 midway through the second half but Judson Wallace, who scored 21 of his 23 points after the break, led a Tigers rally that forged a tie at 64 on Will Venable's layup with 5.6 seconds left in regulation. Schaen's two free throws opened the scoring as the Tigers got the first nine points of the overtime to go up 73-64 with 1:46 remaining. Columbia held a 62-59 lead in regulation when Scott Greenamn hit a 3-pointer from the left corner to tie the score with 1:40 to go. Matt Preston, who had 23 points, made two free throws to put the Lions ahead 64-62 before Venable's layup, after a Columbia turnover, tied the score and forced the overtime. Wallace, who was 13-for-14 at the free throw line, led all five Tigers starters in double figures with Andre Logan scoring 12, Venable and Greenman 11 and Ed Persia 10. Princeton made 29 of 36 free throws while Columbia had 14 attempts, making 11.
